<br>
I must say though that slavery has undergone probably as much revisionism if not more than the holocaust or the indian genocide. The first motion picture ever made is called &quot;Birth of a Nation&quot;. I own a copy. It is quite interesting and humorous to me, kind of like the whitey version of Reefer Madness. In Birth of a Nation, however instead of showing people becoming crazed maniacs from doing pot like Reefer Madness, it showed how the Klan saved the South from the Negro threat. Entertaining now, but probably scary shit to blacks back then. Genocide did occur with the slaves, there are tales of plantation owners committing the final solution before there slaves gained freedom and even before that after Britain banned the slave trade a slaver ship would shackle all there slaves together so that if a British Man-o-war approached they only had to throw one overboard and the rest would all follow. They only had to make one trip out of three or four to make a profit. After they were given there freedom they were still subject to prejudicial juries if they were even given a trial before the mobs lynched them. All it took was for a white to point at a black and make an accusation and he was as good as dead. Hence, the blacks learned to be subservient to whites. <br>
<br>
Yes, I agree that reparations are a virtual impossibility, but we built a holocaust museum for people who we were not responsible for there victimization, and when the idea of using the money owed to the blacks to build an underground railroad museum is brought up many people like to shout about how we don't owe the blacks anything anymore. Isn't it a type of double standard to allow the native americans and jews certain compensations we don't allow blacks?<br>
<br>
Just my perspective.<br>
<br>
Ritt<br>
